UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 1533
1 A RESOLUTION honoring the life and legacy of Dr. Martin Luther King Jr.
2 WHEREAS, this body rightfully honors those Americans whose lives create a
3 cultural and spiritual touchpoint for people across the world, and whose legacies embody
4 the very concepts of justice, truth, and equality; and
5 WHEREAS, Dr. Martin Luther King Jr., being one such American, is duly honored
6 in this chamber on this day; and
7 WHEREAS, Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. was born on January 15, 1929, in Atlanta,
8 Georgia, and was tragically killed on April 4, 1968, in Memphis, Tennessee; and
9 WHEREAS, Dr. King's life traces the very firmament of the struggle for equal
10 rights, a struggle that is very much ongoing more than 50 years after his death; and
11 WHEREAS, from his education at Morehouse College and Boston University to his
12 courageous civil rights work, including the Montgomery bus boycott in 1955, to the
13 March on Washington in 1963, to the historic March from Selma to Montgomery in
14 1965, Dr. King served as a relentless testament to the human spirit's unceasing desire for
15 freedom and equality; and
16 WHEREAS, here in our own Commonwealth, the work of Dr. King and his
17 movement can be seen in myriad ways, particularly with the passage of the Kentucky
18 Civil Rights Act of 1966, which King called "the strongest and most comprehensive civil
19 rights bill passed by a Southern state"; and
20 WHEREAS, now more than ever, Dr. King's belief in change through nonviolence,
21 and his unwavering desire to see a world "sweltering with the heat of oppression
22 transformed into an oasis of peace and justice," is as prudent and necessary as it has ever
23 been; and
24 WHEREAS, now more than ever, Dr. King's dream is a necessary lesson to all
25 women and men across the country—including here in our own Commonwealth—who
26 seek to pursue a life unmarred by the scourge of prejudice; and
27 WHEREAS, it is rightful then that this body pause on this day to commend and
Page 1 of 2
